## **Introduction** {#introduction}

The use of generative AI (GenAI) tools in low- and middle-income countries is multiplying ‚Äì from AI-powered math tutors for children to digital advisory tools for farmers. While studies have shown that such AI-powered applications can be effective at improving development outcomes (e.g., [Henkel et al., 2024](https://arxiv.org/abs/2402.09809)), several have also shown AI applications to exhibit unexpected and unwanted behavior that can be harmful to users (e.g., [Bastani et al., 2024](https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=4895486)).  

Evaluations can address these challenges and help implementers increase their chances of building impactful GenAI products. **While there is broad consensus on the importance of evaluating GenAI in the development sector, there has been little agreement on what this actually means.** In the absence of clear standards, organizations have adopted very different evaluation approaches. On the one hand, some tech-focused organizations emphasize model or product performance evaluations while neglecting impact on development outcomes. On the other hand, development-focused organizations may default to familiar impact evaluation methods like randomized controlled trials (RCTs) while ignoring model and product evaluations. Because of the varied approaches organizations default to in their evaluations, funders also often lack clarity on which evaluations to expect from implementers or what a right-sized, high-quality evaluation entails. And the reality is: **all these methods are complementary and should be used together to answer different questions at different stages of a GenAI product‚Äôs evaluation cycle**. 

This playbook was developed to bring clarity and structure to the evaluation of AI services in the development sector for both funders and service delivery organizations. It aims to define what evaluation of AI applications should entail and highlight a standard set of evaluation practices that implementers should undertake. It is organized around a four-level evaluation framework: 

* **Level 1 ‚Äì Model evaluation**: Does the AI model produce the desired responses? 

* **Level 2 ‚Äì Product evaluation**: Does the product facilitate meaningful interactions? 

* **Level 3 ‚Äì User evaluation**: Does the product positively support users‚Äô thoughts, feelings, knowledge, and behaviors?

* **Level 4 ‚Äì Impact evaluation**: Does access to the product improve development outcomes?

The central element in this framework is the concept of continuous evaluation. Unlike earlier rule-based digital tools, GenAI‚Äôs unique sensitivity to the underlying model, architecture, data, and prompts demands new evaluation methods. Moreover, the underlying components can evolve far faster than in earlier digital technologies. With new AI models and technologies being released weekly, developers must ensure their applications perform as intended over time, even as updates are released. Continuous evaluation thus becomes essential, enabling developers to iterate quickly, maintain expected behavior, and steadily improve performance and impact.

This focus on continuous evaluation, while commonplace in software companies, might be less familiar in the development sector. In the development sector, programs are often judged by one-off experiments where evaluation is treated as the finish line. We believe that evaluation of Generative AI applications should place a greater emphasis on rapid, ongoing cycles, where deployment, adaptation, evaluation, and improvement happen in tandem.

This evaluation framework comes out of lessons from the [AI for Global Development (AI4GD) accelerator](https://agencyfund.notion.site/ai-for-global-development). The Accelerator, led in 2025 by [The Agency Fund](https://www.agency.fund/) (TAF) in collaboration with  [OpenAI](https://openai.com/) and experts at the [Center for Global Development](https://www.cgdev.org/) (CGD) provided an investment of $5 million to support eight non-profit organizations building GenAI products and services across three critical sectors: education (e.g., learning support for students, parents, and teachers), health (e.g., personalized medical advice), and agricultural livelihoods (e.g., agriculture and business advice). This living playbook thus incorporates lessons from accelerator participants and other organizations that have been at the forefront of evaluating GenAI applications for the development sector.

![][image1]

While the four levels of AI evaluation are interconnected and iterative, they often follow a natural progression. An AI model pipeline is first built and its performance benchmarked against general and domain-specific customized metrics (Level 1), then the resulting product or service is tested for usability and user engagement (Level 2). If the tool sees consistent use, we need to understand how it affects users‚Äô thoughts, feelings, knowledge, and short-term behaviors (Level 3\) before assessing whether it drives long-term improvements in development outcomes (Level 4). In the tech sector, evaluation of AI tools typically stops at Levels 1 and 2, because user engagement is often an adequate predictor of product success. But in the development sector, our bar is higher. We‚Äôre not only asking whether people use a tool ‚Äì we‚Äôre also asking whether it improves their lives in meaningful, measurable, and cost-effective ways.

**Frequently asked questions**

* **Who should use this guide?** Ensuring that a GenAI app functions effectively ‚Äì that it engages and supports users, and helps drive development outcomes ‚Äì requires specialists from multiple domains to collaborate. AI engineers tend to focus on model behavior (Level 1); product managers and data scientists on product analytics (Level 2); psychologists and behavioral researchers on user thoughts, feelings, knowledge, and behaviors (Level 3); and impact evaluators on social impact (Level 4). But these divisions can become a barrier in real-world collaborations. *Building better AI for the development sector requires all actors to see beyond their slice of the evaluation process.* This could mean resisting the urge to stop at a strong model benchmark, or to leap straight from a demo to an RCT, without understanding what lies in between. The development and delivery of an effective GenAI service involves continuous evaluation, modification, and improvement. This playbook includes a later section on how to build repeatable, continuous evaluation practices across cross-functional teams. In summary, engineers, product managers, data scientists, psychologists, behavioral researchers, and impact evaluators should use this guide together. 

* **Does this playbook dictate a specific practice or method for evaluating generative AI applications?** This playbook will show multiple approaches to conducting each level of evaluation. It will highlight the pros and cons of each approach. When there are gold standards or particularly proven methodologies, these will be identified.

* **Does this playbook help me identify which level of evaluation my organization should pursue for our AI application?** The playbook will identify what each level of evaluation entails, but there‚Äôs no one-size-fits-all answer. Additionally, we expect that organizations will iteratively return to previous levels as they continue to refine the product. For digitally savvy organizations, model iteration and evaluation are relatively cheap and fast to execute, and your evaluation strategy can evolve and grow quickly. In comparison, user surveys, which are typically found in user and impact evaluations, can be relatively costly and time-consuming due to the need to recruit respondents, design questions, and clean and analyze qualitative responses. The challenge is in deciding which level and intensity of evaluation is appropriate at each stage of a product‚Äôs maturity. The goal is not to always aim for a particular level of evaluation, but to make informed tradeoffs about what constitutes ‚Äúenough‚Äù evaluation, given the context. We will develop a guideline for balancing these tradeoffs in future iterations of the playbook.

* **Are the evaluations described in this playbook all I need to develop a socially impactful product?**  While Levels 1‚Äì3 of evaluation are especially valuable for informing product development, they are *necessary but not sufficient*. Good product development also depends on other critical activities, such as user research, UX design, and content strategy. These workstreams shape how a product functions and feels, and they often run in parallel to, or even ahead of, evaluation activities. For instance, user research, both qualitative and quantitative, is often essential before a product or model is prototyped. These activities help product developers understand user pain points, identify target use cases, define evaluation criteria, and design effective prompts, databases, or knowledge bases. In summary, insights collected prior to evaluation are critical. While many product choices are informed by the evaluation process, user research is especially important early in the process, and in low-data or low-resource settings (where the wrong assumptions can be costly). 

This playbook focuses specifically on **how to do GenAI evaluation well**: what to measure, how to measure it, and how to generate evidence with rigor and speed. It is ***not*** a full product development guide.

In the next phase, we‚Äôll keep updating this playbook and collaborating more deeply with specialists to co-create shared evaluation tools, refine methodologies, and support their practical use in real-world settings.* 

## **Building Blocks for GenAI Evaluation**

Our experience suggests that the success of GenAI products relies on **reusable building blocks that connect and operationalize all four levels of GenAI evaluation in real time**. Unlike traditional development sector interventions, which can be cumbersome to iteratively modify and retest, GenAI allows for precise control over the product‚Äôs configuration, deployment, and monitoring. Like many digital services, GenAI products also enable the passive collection of rich interaction data, creating opportunities to continuously analyze, iterate, and improve. 

For example, the deployment of a GenAI chatbot can be configured to automatically flag when a change in prompt improves model helpfulness (Level 1\) or unexpectedly reduces user trust (Level 3). You can also build model pipelines that flag when a new product feature boosts short-term engagement (Level 2\) but fails to shift long-term outcomes (Level 4). The sort of end-to-end instrumentation that we describe in this playbook allows organizations to move beyond static intervention design and delivery, toward practices that are repeatable and that are embedded in AI product development cycles, and which enable continuous improvement.

What are these building blocks? We lay out below four concrete, actionable steps that move evaluation from theory into practice. 

### 1\. Construct a clear user funnel across Levels 1-4.

One of the most useful motions in AI for the development sector is the construction of a **user funnel** ‚Äì a structured way to map how individuals move through your product or program, from first exposure to long-term life impact. A comprehensive funnel does more than describe the usage of a product; it creates a shared framework for tracking a user‚Äôs experience through a journey. It surfaces weak points along the user journey and creates a common focus for all four levels of evaluation.

To build a robust funnel, teams should begin by defining the **final development outcome** they‚Äôre targeting (Level 4\) ‚Äì for instance, improved learning outcomes, better health, or increased crop yields. From there, work backward to break down the journey into specific **user stages**. A typical funnel includes:

1. **Recruitment** ‚Äì The beneficiary is identified and enters the program. (Level 2\)

2. **Onboarding** ‚Äì The user is introduced to the AI product and completes initial setup. (Level 2\)

3. **Engagement** ‚Äì The user begins actively interacting with the AI product (Level 2). 

4. **Retention** ‚Äì The user continues engaging with the AI product over time, rather than dropping off (Level 2). Level 1 evaluation may continue as needed to monitor model behavior.

5. **Proximal Outcome** ‚Äì The user demonstrates near-term cognitive or behavioral change (Level 3). Level 1 evaluation may continue as needed to monitor model behavior.

6. **Development Outcome** ‚Äì The user achieves the desired long-term result (Level 4).

For each stage, teams should clearly define:

* **What the program does** to bring users into that stage.

* **What the user must do** to count as having entered the stage.

* **The metric** that confirms entry into the stage (e.g., login rate, session length, quiz completion)

* **Target metric values** and **transition rates** between stages.

* **Costs associated with** moving a user through a given stage.

* **DRIs** (Directly Responsible Individuals) for performance and metrics at each stage.

This structure transforms a generic theory of change into a measurable, cost-aware program design tool. It enables product teams to track performance over time, pinpointing user drop-offs or failure points. It exposes how well a user‚Äôs behavior aligns with the product‚Äôs intended outcomes. It also gives funders and evaluators clear indicators of where progress is occurring and where it‚Äôs stalling. For instance, a shift in prompt design (Level 1\) can be traced through to changes in engagement (Level 2), user behavior (Level 3), and finally into human development outcomes (Level 4).

### 2\. Build and track metrics through robust ETL pipelines.

A well-designed evaluation framework is only as good as the data infrastructure that supports it. At the heart of that infrastructure is a robust **ETL pipeline** ‚Äì a system that *extracts, transforms, and loads* data to power consistent, reliable measurement of program indicators.

* **Extract**: Collect data from various sources ‚Äì chat logs, product telemetry, survey tools, third-party APIs, or even spreadsheets.

* **Transform**: Clean, standardize, and reshape the raw data into a usable format. This could involve timestamp alignment, anonymization, session stitching, or deriving new metrics like time-on-task or trust indicators.

* **Load**: Store the transformed data in a centralized system (like a data warehouse or analytics dashboard) where teams can access it for analysis, visualization, or modeling.

AI products, especially those using generative models, produce high volumes of complex, often unstructured data: prompts, outputs, clicks, feedback, engagement patterns, and more. Without a clear ETL pipeline, turning raw data into actionable metrics at scale becomes unreliable and slow. For example, imagine a product designed to support adolescent mental health. It might collect:

* **Model-level outputs (Level 1):** response quality, hallucination rate, representative failure cases.

* **Engagement logs (Level 2):** sessions per user, conversation length, feature use.

* **Behavioral indicators (Level 3):** changes in sentiment or self-reported stress levels.

* **Outcome data (Level 4):** improvement in standardized well-being scores over time.

To make sense of this, the team needs a pipeline that can integrate various data sets ‚Äì raw logs from their Large Language Model (LLM) service, frontend product analytics, periodic user surveys, and outcomes data ‚Äì and then shape them into consistent indicators for each level of evaluation.

### 3\. Diagnose weak links through targeted hypotheses.

Once a user funnel is in place and metrics are flowing through a robust ETL pipeline, the next challenge is understanding why certain funnel metrics are underperforming. We start by identifying major user drop-offs along the funnel: if users are not engaging, they are unlikely to be benefiting from a product. Next, we must explore the causes of the drop-off. This is where **targeted hypotheses** become essential. Rather than jumping to conclusions or relying on intuition, teams can develop targeted hypotheses to pose specific, testable questions about user behavior: *Why are users stalling here?* *What mechanism might explain this drop-off?* *What change could move the needle?* This approach sits at the intersection of product management, UX research, and behavioral science. It acknowledges that while product development is nonlinear, evaluation must remain disciplined and driven by clearly defined learning goals.

Importantly, this doesn't mean evaluation should dictate what teams build; rather, it means that evaluation should clarify what needs to be understood. For example, if engagement dips after onboarding, evaluators might surface competing hypotheses: *Is the product's value proposition unclear?* *Are users overwhelmed by the interface?* *Do they mistrust the AI?* 

Each hypothesis then becomes a lens for focused measurement or experiments, often co-designed with product, user research, and behavioral science leads. This makes evaluation generative: it is not just a judgment of what works, but a process that helps teams ask better questions, faster.

### 4\. Run experiments with rigor and speed.

Once hypotheses are defined, the next step is to test them through experimentation. In the context of GenAI evaluation, experimentation is the bridge between observing a problem and exploring solutions to this problem. Whether it‚Äôs an A/B test, a hold-out test, a pragmatic Randomized Controlled Trial (RCT), or a full-scale RCT, the goal is the same: to generate credible, causal evidence about what interventions improve user outcomes. This step is crucial for turning evaluation from a descriptive activity into a decision-making tool.

Experimentation should be matched to the maturity of the product, the scale of the hypothesis, what is at stake, and the type of decision at hand. For lightweight product tweaks like changing a prompt or onboarding message, A/B tests are often the fastest and most cost-effective approach. For more complex behavioral shifts or policy-relevant questions, teams might deploy staggered rollouts or holdout-based designs. In some cases, a full RCT may be warranted, but only when the causal question justifies the cost.

Across AI4GD teams, we‚Äôve seen experimentation work best when it‚Äôs integrated into ongoing development. Structured templates, clear success metrics, and tools like [**Evidential**](https://docs.evidential.dev/welcome/) help teams automate randomization, track real-time results, and reduce analysis bottlenecks. More importantly, a culture of experimentation creates room for continuous learning. Each result, positive or not, refines the product, sharpens the theory of change, and builds institutional knowledge.

## **Building Cross-Functional Teams**

Building effective GenAI evaluation practices is fundamentally a **team sport**. No single role can cover all four evaluation levels ‚Äì success comes from a cross-functional team in which each member understands their responsibilities and how they complement others. In leading tech companies, AI product teams are deliberately cross-functional: *AI engineers focus on model development, data scientists on analytics, user researchers on human factors, scientists to measure downstream outcomes, and product managers tie everything together*. Adopting this approach in the development sector helps avoid silos and ensures that improvements at one level translate into progress at others. Below, we outline the typical roles at each level, how they collaborate, the tools that support them, and ways to align team goals with evaluation outcomes.

| Evaluation Level | Key Roles | Core Responsibilities |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **Level 1 ‚Äì Model** | **Lead:** Al Engineers; ML Researchers **Support:** Domain Experts; Product Owners | Build and fine-tune models; run offline tests; ensure relevance and safety; log outputs for downstream use. Domain-specific inputs (e.g., educators for tutor bots) are also essential. |
| **Level 2 ‚Äì Product** | **Lead:** Product Managers **Support:** Data Scientists; Data Engineers | Integrate AI into workflows; track engagement through A/B tests; maintain shared dashboards; align usage data with user behavior and product design. |
| **Level 3 ‚Äì User** | **Lead:** Psychologists; UX Researchers **Support:** Data Scientists | Measure user outcomes (cognitive, affective, and behavioral) and run A/B tests on these outcomes; run surveys and interviews; co-design metrics with end users; and integrate qualitative insights with usage data. |
| **Level 4 ‚Äì Impact** | **Lead:** Policy Researchers; Data Scientists; Economists **Support:** Al Engineers | Evaluate long-term outcomes (e.g., learning, health, income); define theory of change; run impact evaluations |

*Note: In small teams, one person may wear multiple hats across these levels. What matters is that **all four perspectives are represented**. For instance, an AI engineer might initially also gather user feedback, but they should still seek input from a behavioral researcher or domain specialist to fill Level 3 considerations. Likewise, product managers should be conversant in model metrics, and researchers should understand product constraints. The team should collectively decide what ‚Äúenough evaluation‚Äù looks like at each stage.*

From our experiences working with AI4GD organizations, here are the broader **best practices** that we‚Äôd recommend for cross-level collaboration in GenAI evaluation projects.

**1\. Look Beyond Your Slices of Evaluation**

Every team member should understand how their work affects other levels of evaluation. For instance, AI engineers should go beyond benchmarks and ask product or research teams if the model improves user experience. A data scientist looking at engagement (Level 2\) might learn more by talking to a behavioral expert (Level 3). Regular cross-functional check-ins focused on the user journey help spot these connections and prevent tunnel vision.

**2\. Pair Engineers with Domain Experts Early**

Involve domain experts at Level 1 (model evaluation) from the start. Model builders need input from those who understand user needs ‚Äì teachers, doctors, researchers ‚Äì to define success beyond technical metrics. This ensures evaluations reflect what really matters for users.

**3\. Identify a Cross-Functional Lead**

Product Managers (or cross-functional leads) should connect the dots across roles, coordinate timelines, facilitate experiments, and translate insights into decisions. An evaluation plan outlining how a feature will be tested across Levels 1‚Äì4 keeps the team aligned on goals and evidence.

**4\. Use a Shared Evaluation Language**

Adopt a common vocabulary using levels (e.g., ‚ÄúLevel 1: better model accuracy, Level 2: more engagement, Level 3: better learning gains, Level 4: better literacy outcomes‚Äù). Explain technical jargon to your teammates when necessary. Document what‚Äôs been tested and learned in a shared space. This builds memory across the team and avoids reinventing the wheel.

**5\. Use Tools that Support Collaboration**

* **Evaluation Platform**: A concentrated GenAI evaluation platform can help track model behavior and user impact in one place.

* **Dashboards & Data Pipelines**: Centralized, annotated dashboards can ensure that key metrics are accessible to all.

* **Experimentation Platform**: Use lightweight tools (e.g., Evidential to run and track experiments collaboratively.

* **Project & Knowledge Tools**: Keep tasks visible, foster quick feedback, and hold regular debriefs for deeper insights.

## 

## **Level 1 ‚Äì Model Evaluation**: Does the AI model produce the desired responses? {#level-1-‚Äì-model-evaluation:-does-the-ai-model-produce-the-desired-responses?}

*Note: Sections marked with ü§ñ provide technical sidebars or additional detail that you can skip if you like. Some of the content requires background knowledge, and we provide this in boxes marked with ‚óÄÔ∏è.*

### Why is this level of evaluation important?

AI models, especially large language models (LLMs) and related foundational models, do not ‚Äú[understand](https://www.sciencenews.org/article/ai-large-language-model-understanding?utm_source=chatgpt.com)‚Äù content in the way humans do. Instead, they generate outputs by predicting the next word in a sequence based on statistical patterns in their training data. Because of this, models can **hallucinate** or appear fluent and convincing while still being inaccurate, biased, irrelevant, or even harmful.

This makes structured model evaluation essential. We need to systematically and rigorously assess whether an AI system consistently meets conditions such as usefulness, accuracy, appropriateness, and safety across diverse tasks and user contexts. This is especially critical when AI tools are deployed in sensitive domains like education, health, or agriculture, where misinformation or misalignment can cause real harm. 

Beyond ensuring safety, developers must also evaluate that their AI systems exhibit desirable behaviors and characteristics proven to have a real-world impact. For instance, an AI tutor should follow pedagogical best practices ‚Äì such as withholding answers to encourage self-directed learning and accurately gauging a student‚Äôs level to tailor instruction. This level of assessment focuses on verifying that the AI exhibits these specific, beneficial behaviors.

| ‚óÄÔ∏è What is the ‚Äúmodel‚Äù in ‚Äúmodel evaluations‚Äù? The term "model" is often ambiguous. In AI development, it can refer to two very different things:1\. The Foundational Model (The "Engine"): This is the underlying large-scale model itself, trained on vast data. Examples: GPT-4, Llama 3, Gemini 2.5 2\. The End-to-End System (The "Car"): This is the *entire application* you build. It includes the foundational model *plus* all the other components that make it work for a user. Examples: Your full pipeline, which might include: Retrieving the right information from a knowledge base  System prompts and pre-processing, like translation or speech-to-text The foundational model's generation Safety guardrails and post-processing, like translation or text-to-speech When we say "model," we are referring to the End-to-End System (Definition 2). To avoid confusion, we will always use the term "foundational model" when referring to the engine (Definition 1). |
| :---- |

### 

### What is being assessed under model evaluation?

Most Generative AI applications, whether for health, livelihood, or education, are built on foundational models like those from OpenAI (GPT), Anthropic (Claude), Google (Gemini), or Meta (Llama).

However, your application is a full system, not just the foundational model. It includes many other components that can be grouped into three buckets:

* **Pre-processing:** Before handing off the input from the user to the LLM, you may wish to transform it into a format suitable for the LLM. Some examples of pre-processing components are: (a) sanitizing or filtering language; (b) converting speech to text; (c) paraphrasing the user‚Äôs request; (d) translation from a low-resource language to a high-resource one. 

* **LLM context preparation:** An LLM takes three things as input: (a) the ‚Äúprompt‚Äù  or the system instructions, (b) the user‚Äôs input after being pre-processed, and (c) a ‚Äúcontext‚Äù which can include past conversation history, relevant content retrieved from your knowledge base, or even tools available for the LLM to call. You may have more than one of these components.

* **Post-processing:** Before returning the output to the user, you may also wish to again transform it into the correct format and check the output using safety or quality guardrails. Some examples of post-processing components are: (a) hallucination checker, (b) converting text to speech, (c) translation to the user‚Äôs preferred language

For example, an AI agronomist in Senegal, answering questions from farmers in Pulaar, might:

* (a) check the input for malicious intent or off-topic content 

* (b) translate from Pulaar to English 

* (c) retrieve relevant content from the database 

* (d) retrieve information about the farmer 

* (e) generate an answer 

* (f) check that the answer is grounded in the content shared with the LLM 

* (g) translate back to Pulaar. 

In this example, (a) and (b) are part of the pre-processing, (c), (d), and (e) are LLM context-preparation, and (f) and (g) are post-processing steps.

| ‚óÄÔ∏è Low- vs high-resource languages Many AI systems are used in contexts where users speak low-resource languages such as Kannada or Hikuyu. These languages have relatively less digitized text and fewer labeled datasets available in the training of large AI models, which means the model may hallucinate more often. In contrast, high-resource languages like English or Hindi have far more data representation, leading to stronger accuracy. To improve performance, systems may translate the user‚Äôs input from a low-resource language to a high-resource one, generate the response in the language where the model performs best, then translate the answer back so the user receives guidance in the language they prefer. |
| :---- |

**Model evaluations cover this entire pipeline**. They assess your complete solution, from the user's input to the final output, to verify it exhibits desirable behavior. While you can (and should) test individual components using unit tests, that process is outside the scope of this document.

### AI solutions can also take many forms. They can be chatbots, voice agents that you can converse with in real-time, or agents that take action, like filling out our forms or calling external services. **Model evaluations cover all of these different modalities**. 

| ‚óÄÔ∏è Benchmarking vs. evaluations Evaluation focuses on *your* requirements \- ‚Äúdoes my solution meet my goals‚Äù \- whereas benchmarking answers ‚Äúdoes my solution do well on a public metric‚Äù. You may look at benchmark results when choosing what foundational model to use. Benchmarks can provide some guidance on how well different models and products can perform certain tasks, but are rarely sufficient to evaluate if your solution works in your context. We don‚Äôt cover benchmarking here and focus instead on evaluation ‚Äì i.e., how to check your solution against your criteria. |
| :---- |

### How do we evaluate GenAI models?

The figure below describes the steps in a model evaluation:	

1. **Decide on your rubric:** Product owners must answer the question ‚Äúwhat characteristics are important for your AI solution to exhibit?‚Äù. For example, an AI agronomist might care about accuracy, whereas a mental health bot might care about ‚Äúempathy‚Äù. 

2. **Decide on metrics:** The engineers decide on methods to measure or *score* how your solution performs against items on your rubric.

3. **Develop a golden dataset:** The engineers develop a dataset that is representative of the kinds of interactions real users will have. The dataset is used to score the solution using the metrics determined previously as it is refined.

4. **Run automated evaluations:** You can set up automated processes to calculate your metrics at regular intervals or when triggered by certain events.

5. **Measure scores and refine solution:** You can use the scores generated by your evaluation to know if your solution is improving in dimensions you care about. If scores are satisfactory, the evaluated version of your solution is ready to be deployed. If not, there is a refinement step to diagnose points of failure and improve the solution. This evaluation-measurement-refinement loop may require a few cycles before the solution is ready to be deployed. 

6. **Red-teaming:** Beyond evaluating your solution against known criteria (your golden dataset), you may also want to actively try to break or pressure test it before releasing it into the wild

The rest of this section will be structured around these steps in the blue box labelled ‚ÄúOFFLINE EVALUATION PROCESS‚Äù. We reference some of the components in the green box labelled ‚ÄúONLINE EVALUATION PROCESS‚Äù when we discuss developing a golden dataset.

| ‚óÄÔ∏è Online evaluation vs. Offline evaluations The green box in the diagram above shows that even after your solution has been deployed, you should continue to filter outputs through guardrails to ensure safety and maintain adherence to your rubric. You should also implement logging or ‚Äútracing‚Äù for the inputs and outputs of various components in your pipeline. By monitoring these traces, you are able to identify new and unexpected ways your users may be interacting with your solution and failure modes not encountered during offline evaluation. These should be used to augment your golden dataset and refine the solution. Though we will reference online evaluations where relevant, we will not be providing guidance on how to do them well. We will leave it for future extension of this playbook and other guides \[OPEN DISCUSSION: For expert discussion on whether to include\]. |
| :---- |

1\. Decide on a rubric

\---

**Responsible:** Product Owners and Domain Experts. 

The Product Owner is accountable for the project's business goals. They, along with domain experts, are responsible for defining the qualitative characteristics of a successful solution (e.g., ‚ÄúTrustworthy‚Äù, ‚ÄúOn-Brand‚Äù, ‚ÄúConcise‚Äù).

**Support**: Engineering

The engineering team must understand the intent behind each rubric item. This context is critical to ensure that the metrics selected in the next step are technically feasible and accurately map to the product owner‚Äôs qualitative goals.

\---

The first step in level 1 evals is to come up with your evaluation rubric. Solution owners need to answer the question: *‚ÄúWhat characteristics should our AI solution embody?‚Äù*. These are qualitative goals. For example, a characteristic that may be important to you is ‚ÄúTrustworthiness‚Äù. 

Though there are some essential things your solution should embody, most of the rubric will be determined by your use case, context, and impact goals. This step often takes lots of reflection and discussion about stakeholders to get right. It is a critical step that guides the rest of your evaluation steps, and implementers should not rush this step.

##### Case Studies

[Jacaranda Health (JH)](https://jacarandahealth.org/) pioneers the use of generative AI to transform how underserved mothers in Sub-Saharan Africa access, understand, and act on vital maternal and newborn health information. Their product (PROMPTS) is a two-way SMS service designed to promote positive care-seeking behaviors amongst new and expectant mothers through timely health information and support throughout the pregnancy and postpartum journey. Responses are generated by Jacaranda‚Äôs customized LLM, UlizaLlama, which is based on Meta‚Äôs Llama2 and fine-tuned for use in Swahili and English ([Stanford Center for Digital Health, 2025](https://cdh.stanford.edu/our-research-portfolio/generative-ai-health-low-middle-income-countries)). The evaluation of PROMPT‚Äôs LLM responses at Level 1 is based on rubrics for ‚Äúmedical accuracy and appropriateness, personability, and simplicity.‚Äù

Another example comes from [Digital Green (DG)](https://digitalgreen.org/), which uses GenAI to democratize access to localized, actionable agricultural knowledge for smallholder farmers across Africa and Asia. Their product (Farmer.Chat) is a multilingual, multimodal conversational platform that delivers personalized, context-aware agricultural advice through familiar messaging apps like WhatsApp and Telegram. Built using a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) architecture and integrated with a dynamic knowledge base of expert-vetted documents, videos, and real-time data, Farmer.Chat provides reliable guidance on more than 40 crops across four countries (Kenya, India, Ethiopia, and Nigeria). Responses are generated by Digital Green‚Äôs custom large language model pipeline, optimized for low-literacy users and localized languages including Swahili, Amharic, Hausa, Hindi, Odiya, Telugu, and English. The model synthesizes structured and unstructured agricultural data to produce clear, trustworthy, and culturally relevant information delivered via text, voice, and video formats. Hence, the evaluation of Farmer.Chat‚Äôs performance at Level 1is based on rubrics for ‚Äúfaithfulness, relevance, and accessibility‚Äù ([Singh et al., 2024](https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.08916)).

**How many dimensions should I have in my rubric?**

It is tempting to make a long list of characteristics you want. After all, you want your model to not just be trustworthy but also friendly, on-brand, concise, complete, curious, empathetic, encouraging, direct, and so many other things. Unfortunately, the longer this list, the more expensive and difficult your evaluation process. There are also often tradeoffs between them that are hard to get right (e.g, concise vs. complete, friendly vs. direct). We recommend that you restrict the rubric to around 5 items.

#### 2\. Decide on metrics

\---

**Responsible:** *Engineering.* 

This team is responsible for translating the qualitative rubric into a set of quantitative, measurable metrics (e.g., mapping "Trustworthy" to "Factual Consistency Score"). They own the technical selection and implementation of the scorers.

**Support**: *Product owners* or *domain experts* 

The Product Owner must review and validate the proposed metrics. Their role is to confirm that the selected technical metrics (e.g., "BLEU score") are acceptable and accurate proxies for the intended business goals (e.g., "Conciseness").

\---

| ‚óÄÔ∏è Rubric, Metrics, Scorers *A rubric item maps to one or more metrics. A Scorer returns a quantitative score on how well a solution performs against a metric.* For example, one of your rubric items may be ‚Äúhelpful‚Äù. One of the metrics this maps to may be ‚Äúanswer relevance‚Äù. And then you might use a scorer like ‚ÄúLLM-as-judge‚Äù to produce a score for this metric, say ‚Äú4 out of 5‚Äù.  Though there are other synonymous terms, we‚Äôll use these terms throughout this section for consistency and clarity. |
| :---- |

Now that you have your rubric, you need to figure out what *scorers* and *metrics* you will use to track against each of the dimensions of your rubric. Scorers available fall under one of three categories, each with its own pros and cons:

| Category | Example scorers | Example use-case | Pros / Cons |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| *Statistical scorers* These are based on the words in the LLM output and don‚Äôt take the semantic meaning into account. | [BLEU](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BLEU), [ROUGE](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ROUGE_\(metric\)), [METEOR](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/METEOR), [WER](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Word_error_rate) | An NGO evaluates a literacy chatbot that generates short reading comprehension questions in Swahili. BLEU and ROUGE are used to compare the chatbot‚Äôs questions to a set of human-written reference questions to assess linguistic overlap. | Speed: \+++++Accuracy: \++Cost (lower is better): \+ |
| *Model-based scorers* These are small language models trained to do one specific task. | [AlignScore](https://github.com/yuh-zha/AlignScore)/[LIM-RA](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2404.06579), [BLEURT](https://github.com/google-research/bleurt), [BARTScore](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2106.11520), [COMET](https://unbabel.github.io/COMET/html/index.html),  | A health information NGO uses BLEURT, a pre-trained model designed to score text quality, to evaluate the responses of an AI assistant that explains vaccination schedules to parents. The model-based scorer assesses how semantically faithful and understandable each generated message is compared to a trusted reference explanation. | Speed: \+++Accuracy: \+++Cost (lower is better): \+++ |
| *LLM-based scorers a.k.a LLM-as-judge* Since they use LLMs, they are flexible and powerful. But it can also be expensive and slow. | [G-Eval](https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.16634), [RARR](https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.08726) | A digital agriculture platform uses a large language model (LLM) as a judge to evaluate the quality of pest management advice generated by smaller domain models. Using G-Eval, the LLM scores each message for accuracy, clarity, and farmer-friendliness, comparing them to expert agronomist responses. | Speed: \++Accuracy: \+++++Cost (lower is better): \+++++ |
| *Human evaluation*For tasks requiring nuances and complex reasoning, or detecting subtle hallucinations, humans are ideal \-- though not without their [own](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2307.03025) [biases](https://github.com/huggingface/evaluation-guidebook/blob/main/contents/human-evaluation/basics.md). | [Human evaluation](https://github.com/huggingface/evaluation-guidebook/blob/main/contents/human-evaluation/basics.md) | A mental health NGO tests a GenAI counseling tool for youth. Human evaluators (e.g., psychologists and peer mentors) manually rate the empathy, appropriateness, and emotional resonance of responses. | Speed: \+ Accuracy: \+++++ Cost (lower is better): \++++++ |

The examples given above are hardly comprehensive. This is an active area of research, and newer methods are being developed all the time. But these should give you a broad sense of the kinds of methods that exist. Each has its pros and cons, so the ideal metrics are a combination of these. 

| ü§ñDeciding between metrics Note that statistical and model-based scorers are designed for very specific tasks. For example, COMET is used for machine translation, AlignScore is for factual consistency, and WER is for speech recognition. You can only use them for those tasks. It also helps to know their weaknesses. For example, BLEU only checks for precision, i.e., the number of words in the candidate sentence that are also in the reference. Even with LLM-as-judge scorers, there are multiple options. You can just prompt an LLM, use chain-of-thought, or, for checking hallucinations, break down the response into a set of claims and check each one against a reference text. Also, there is [some evidence](https://aclanthology.org/2024.findings-naacl.148.pdf) that some LLM-as-judge methods don‚Äôt work so well for low-resourced languages.Finally, there's the Human-as-judge. While human raters are the gold standard for catching subtle nuance and contextual failures that automated methods miss, they are also slow, expensive, and suffer from their [own biases](https://github.com/huggingface/evaluation-guidebook/blob/main/contents/human-evaluation/basics.md). Because of this, their primary role is not to score your entire dataset, but to perform two critical, high-leverage jobs: first, to create the small "answer key" used to calibrate your automated LLM-as-judge (as we'll see next), and second, to act as a final quality assurance check on high-stakes examples before a major launch.Hope this sidebar has convinced you that there is no getting around deeply understanding each of the methods in order to pick the right ones.  |
| :---- |

	The engineering team needs to pick the right metric (or multiple metrics) for each of the items on your rubric and a scorer to produce that metric. 

| ü§ñIs my LLM-as-judge working? To know if your LLM-as-judge is working, you need to see if it aligns with scores humans would give. Here‚Äôs an example of how you do this for a maternal health question answering  Create a small set of, say, 100-200 outputs.  Have 3 humans score them against a rubric that is important to you, e.g., helpfulness.  Calculate the Inter-Rater Reliability (IRR) between these. If you get a low score, then you need to work on calibration and clearly define what ‚Äúhelpful‚Äù really means.  If you get a high IRR, run your LLM-as-judge against these 100 outputs. Check the correlation between the LLM‚Äôs score and your human raters If high (\> 0.8), you‚Äôre set\! You can feel confident using your LLM-as-judge to score your outputs If low, you need to improve your LLM-as-judge: better prompt, adding ‚Äúfew-shot‚Äù examples, using more advanced methods, etc. Go back to 5\. |
| :---- |

#### Case Studies

Jacaranda Health recently added voice capabilities to its services, aiming to help mothers who have difficulty reading or seeing text to access its content. By using voice, these mothers can access important health information more easily. For data collection, Jacaranda Health initially used audio samples from Mozilla Common Voice. However, this source had too many male voices and was not specific to their needs. They worked to collect a more representative sample of voices from their users, taking into account the various accents throughout Kenya.

![][image2]

They set out to bring voice‚Äëbased maternal care to women who struggle with text. They recorded a balanced Swahili‚ÄëEnglish voice corpus from rural and urban mothers across Kenya, then fine‚Äëtuned OpenAI‚Äôs Whisper model on that data. Over successive iterations, they drove Word Error Rate (WER) down from 87‚ÄØpercent to 15‚ÄØpercent, inching toward their 6‚ÄØpercent target that matches top‚Äëtier languages. Hitting each new milestone meant trading off between the volume of diverse accents in the training set and the computing and annotation budget they had available.

Standard WER simply tallies substitutions, insertions, and deletions without regard for meaning. That metric penalizes Swahili‚Äôs flexible word order and complex verb forms even when the intent is clear. To get a truer picture of how well mothers can follow advice, Jacaranda now measures **semantic accuracy using a cosine-similarity-based WER**. This approach rewards transcripts that convey the same health guidance, even if they differ in exact phrasing. Hence, it is a good example of having to invent non-standard metrics to get AI working for their context.

In a similar vein, to benchmark Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) models in agriculture, Digital Green also used metrics such as Word Error Rate (WER), Character Error Rate (CER), and Match Error Rate (MER), but had to introduce **a custom Agri‚ÄëWeighted WER** that penalizes errors in key agricultural terms more heavily. This evaluation framework helps identify which models are production‚Äëready and where fine‚Äëtuning is needed. Using weighted metrics, they track progress across Hindi, Telugu, and Odiya datasets and tailor improvements to support scalable, farmer‚Äëfocused advisory systems.

#### 

#### 3\. Develop a golden dataset  \---

**Responsible:** *Product Owner* 

The Product Owner is accountable for the final quality, scope, and representativeness of this dataset. They must ensure it accurately reflects the expected user interactions and sufficiently covers critical use cases and potential failure modes.

**Support:** *Domain Experts and Engineering*

Domain Experts are essential for authoring the ‚Äúgolden‚Äù or ideal answers. The engineering team provides technical support by sourcing data (e.g., from past transaction data) and managing the dataset's infrastructure.

\---

Now you have:

* The **rubric** that defines qualities of the solution that product owners think are critical.

* The **metrics** that tell you how you are doing against each item in the rubric.

* The **scorers** you will use will get a score for each of these metrics.

As you develop and refine our solution, you want to ensure it is improving in the dimensions you have identified. You need a set of records that look like the real user interactions your solution will receive. You can then use this ‚Äúgolden dataset‚Äù to track how well different versions of your solution perform against your metrics. This is often the hardest and most time-consuming part of the evaluation process. Let‚Äôs list out a few ways you can create this dataset:

**From past transaction data:** If you are adding AI to an existing application, you may have data from the current non-AI version of your application. For example, say your user queries were being answered by humans, and you are building an AI feature to take the first pass at answering the user‚Äôs query. You may be able to extract question-answer pairs from past data. 

\[PLACEHOLDER: Momconnect example in development\]

**Human-annotated data:** If you are building an entirely new AI offering or the previous version was not digital, you won‚Äôt have past data to lean on. In that case, you may need to generate (a) questions that you expect your users to ask (b) official answers to these questions from subject matter experts.

Guessing what questions users will ask is not easy. You may be able to crowdsource a few from real users, and then use an LLM to generate other questions in a similar tone and language. Your subject matter experts may also be able to suggest questions. 

Once you have these sets of questions, you need to source the ideal answer to each of these. Unfortunately, those best placed to generate these answers are often scarce and expensive resources (probably why you are automating some of their work), e.g., Nurses, agriculture tech advisors, tutors. There is a temptation to use an LLM to generate the answers and the experts to just verify or correct them. We‚Äôd highly recommend against that. Humans love shortcuts, and correcting answers is often more work than just accepting an answer. This can lead to a low-quality golden dataset that can jeopardize your entire evaluation process.

\[PLACEHOLDER: Intelehealth example in development\]

**Customize public datasets:** If a high-quality public dataset exists that closely matches your use case, it can serve as a starting point. You can subset the large dataset to select only the most relevant examples, and then augment them to better reflect your specific context. 

#### Characteristics of a good golden dataset

Ideally, you want the dataset to cover the full range of the kinds of interactions you may receive and support.

(a) **types of questions users will ask** \- not just *what* the users will ask, but also *how* they will ask it. The ‚Äúhow‚Äù would include not just modality (e.g., voice, text) but also the tone, language, and code-switching, informality, spelling errors, level of verbosity, etc. 

(b) **out of context requests** \- you also want to have questions that your AI application does not support to ensure that you are handling these the right way. These might be off-topic requests or on-topic, but a type of request you don‚Äôt want to handle, e.g, ‚Äúwrite me a poem about maternal health‚Äù.

(c) **adversarial or malicious requests** \- you should also have some examples of malicious interactions. These could be examples of abusive input, prompt injection, jailbreaking, and data & privacy attacks.

| ü§ñ Keeping your golden dataset up to date No matter how thorough your planning, your users will find new and surprising ways to interact with your system \- queries and inputs you simply didn't expect. That's why you need an observability tool. Popular options include Logfire, Helicone, and Langfuse, but there are many others, and we leave it to you and your engineering team to pick one. Many of these products also have the bonus of letting you track and visualize your evaluation results (see next section). By reviewing these interaction "traces," you can spot new patterns, different user request types, and, critically, new failure modes. You should then add these new examples to your "golden dataset" to improve its coverage and representativeness. |
| :---- |

#### 

#### 4\. Running Automated Evals

\---

**Responsible:** Engineering 

The engineering team is responsible for the complete technical implementation of the evaluation pipeline. This includes integrating the evals into the CI/CD process, managing their execution and frequency, and ensuring the results are reliable and accessible.

**Support**: Product Owner

The Product Owner is the primary consumer of the evaluation results. They support this process by actively monitoring the performance trends over time, using the data to track progress.

\---

Running these evaluations manually is quite tedious, not scalable, and introduces inconsistency. Instead, you should automate this process and integrate it directly into your engineering team's workflow.

**Integrate with CI/CD:** The evaluation suite should be integrated into your CI/CD (Continuous Integration/Continuous Deployment) pipeline. This automation ensures that all code changes are validated against your performance criteria before being merged, preventing regressions.

**Strategize Evaluation Frequency:** Evaluation methods vary significantly in computational and token cost. A tiered approach balances cost and information.

* **Low-Cost Evals:** Statistical scorers (e.g., ROUGE) and many model-based scorers are fast and inexpensive. These should be run frequently, ideally on every code commit, to provide rapid feedback. But as we noted above, they are limited in what they can measure.

* **High-Cost Evals:** LLM-as-judge scorers can be much more comprehensive but computationally intensive and can incur significant token costs. Their execution can be less frequent. Common triggers include nightly builds, weekly schedules, or as a final validation step before a major release.

**Track Performance Over Time:** Evaluation is a continuous process. Use your observability tool (e.g., Logfire, Helicone, Langfuse) to plot your metric scores over time. This dashboard provides a critical view for product owners to track progress against rubric goals and verify that solution changes are yielding measurable improvements.  
\[PLACEHOLDER: Case study in development\]

#### 5\. Measure scores and refine the solution

\---  
**Responsible:** Engineering. 

Following an evaluation, the engineering team is responsible for analyzing the results. They must diagnose the root cause of low scores or regressions (e.g., via trace analysis) and then propose and implement technical solutions for refinement.

**Support:** Product Owner

The Product Owner reviews the engineering analysis and is responsible for prioritizing the refinement work. They must weigh the business impact of a given metric (e.g., a drop in "Factual Accuracy" vs. "Friendliness") against the engineering cost to address it.

\---

It is expected that initial evaluation scores will reveal areas for improvement. The results are not a final grade but a diagnostic tool to guide the refinement process.

**Isolate the Problem:** A modern AI solution has many components (e.g., retrieval, prompting, model parameters). A poor score indicates an issue, but not its source. The first step is to identify which component is contributing to the failure.

**Use Traces for Diagnosis:** Observability traces are essential for this diagnosis. A trace captures the end-to-end execution of a request from your golden dataset, allowing the team to inspect the inputs and outputs of each component. This view helps an engineer pinpoint the root cause, such as ineffective document retrieval in a RAG system or a poorly structured prompt.

| ü§ñ What is a ‚Äútrace‚Äù?A trace is the complete, end-to-end record of a single request as it moves through every part of your AI application. A trace would typically include: Input and outputs to each component: For the answering generation component in an AI Agronomist, this may be the user query, the content retrieved from the knowledge base, and the answer generated. Model & Parameters: E.g., Which language model (e.g., GPT-4o) and what settings were used (e.g., temperature: 0.7, max\_tokens: 1024\) Cost & Usage: How many tokens were used and how much the request cost When LLM gives an incorrect or unexpected answer, a trace lets you diagnose what happened. Since LLMs are non-deterministic (they can give different answers to the same input), logging and monitoring these traces are critical. |
| :---- |

### 

**Implement Component-Level Unit Tests:** In addition to the system-level evaluations from your golden dataset, you should implement unit tests for individual components of your pipeline. These granular tests validate specific pieces of logic and help catch regressions at a more foundational level.

| ü§ñ Unit Tests vs. Golden Dataset Evals. It is important to differentiate between these two testing methods: Golden Dataset Eval (Integration Test): Assesses the *entire system* on a qualitative, end-to-end goal. For example: "Does the solution provide a 'helpful' answer to this complex user query?" Unit Test: Assesses a *single component* for a specific, expected behavior. For example: "Does the \`extract\_user\_intent\` function correctly return 'purchase' when the input is 'buy shoes'?" A robust testing strategy requires both. Your high-level golden dataset evals identify *what* the problem is (the symptom), while traces and unit tests help your team diagnose *where* the problem is (the cause). We don‚Äôt talk about good unit testing practices in detail here, though numerous software engineering books like The Pragmatic Programmer or Software Engineering at Google provide useful guidance. |
| :---- |

#### 

#### 6\. Red-teaming your solution

\---

**Responsible:** Product Owner

As the individual accountable for the solution's safety and reliability, the Product Owner is responsible for ensuring red-teaming is conducted. This includes allocating the necessary time and resources for the effort and prioritizing the remediation of any discovered vulnerabilities.

**Support:** Engineering, QA, or a specialized Security/Ethics Team

This adversarial testing is executed by technical teams. Their responsibility is to systematically probe the system for flaws, adopt the mindset of a malicious user, and document their findings.

\---

	Beyond evaluating your solution against known criteria (your golden dataset), you may also want to actively try to break or pressure test it before releasing it into the wild. This is the goal of red-teaming.

**What is red-teaming?**

Red-teaming is a form of structured, adversarial testing. While your golden dataset evaluates how your solution performs on expected inputs, red-teaming is the practice of purposefully probing for unexpected and undesired behaviors.

The goal is to proactively discover vulnerabilities, biases, potential for misuse, and other failure modes before your users do. This involves thinking like a malicious actor, a confused user, or simply a creative edge-case generator to see if you can make the system behave in ways it shouldn't.

**When should we do red-teaming?**

While all solutions can benefit from some red-teaming, it is critically important in specific scenarios. You should strongly prioritize red-teaming for:

* **Agentic or Highly Flexible Solutions:** The more freedom and capability your solution has (e.g., to browse the web, execute code, or make multi-step decisions), the more pathways exist for it to fail. Increased autonomy demands increased adversarial testing.

* **Use Cases with Long Conversation Histories:** Solutions that maintain context over long interactions (like a mental health companion or a tutor bot) are susceptible to cumulative errors. A small issue in turn 1 could be amplified by turn 10\. Red-teaming should test these long-term interactions to see if they drift into unsafe or nonsensical territory.

* **High-Risk Domains:** If your solution operates in a high-stakes environment (e.g., maternal health, medical advice, financial planning), the impact of a failure is severe. Red-teaming is non-negotiable here to identify and mitigate any potential for harm.

* **Population-Scale Solutions:** When deploying a solution to a large, diverse, and anonymous user base, you must assume two things:

  1. You do not know all the ways your users will interact with the system.

  2. At a high enough scale ($N$), even the most improbable ("weird") behaviors will occur.  
     Red-teaming helps you anticipate and build resilience against the sheer unpredictability of a large user population.

**How do you do red-teaming**

At a minimum, red-teaming should follow three steps: **Plan ‚Üí Probe ‚Üí Prioritize.**

**1\. Plan.**  
	Define your goal (what kinds of failures you‚Äôre looking for), choose who will test (mix of technical and domain experts), and decide where to test (model API, product UI, or both).

**2\. Probe.**  
	Adopt an adversarial mindset: try to confuse, exploit, or stress-test the system. Look for ways the model might produce unsafe, biased, or nonsensical responses ‚Äì especially in long conversations or sensitive domains. Capture each failure example with its input, output, and context.

**3\. Prioritize.**

Review findings by severity and likelihood, assign owners for fixes, and rerun the tests after mitigations. Document what worked and what still needs monitoring.

For practical templates and sample prompts, see:

* [*Red-Teaming AI for Social Good Playbook*](https://humane-intelligence.org/insights/research/#:~:text=UNESCO's%20Red%20Teaming%20Playbook%20is,promote%20ethical%20and%20inclusive%20AI.) (UNESCO & Human Intelligence, 2024\)

* [*Planning Red-Teaming for Large Language Models*](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/openai/concepts/red-teaming) (Microsoft Learn, 2024\)

### **Level 2 ‚Äì Product evaluation**: Does the product facilitate meaningful interactions?

### Why is this level of evaluation important?

Beyond evaluating how the AI model performs against key metrics, organizations need to assess how well the product engages real users and whether it solves a meaningful problem for the user. It is unlikely that a product will shift development outcomes if it fails to engage its users. Like model evaluation, this type of evaluation is a continuous and iterative process, rather than one-off.

Technology companies frequently evaluate and improve products by collecting user interaction metrics and then running rapid cycles of digital experiments. For example, they may track a user‚Äôs journey on a website, automatically collecting records like which products the users click on and whether they return to the site. Then, they can compare how different web or app experiences affect browsing time or user satisfaction. This rapid, iterative process is enabled by two factors unique to digital interventions:

1. iterations of the product can be precisely and efficiently deployed to different users and

2. on-platform engagement outcomes are costless to collect and transform into meaningful engagement metrics. 

### 

### Who is most involved in this level of evaluation?

| Product Managers | Data Scientists | Engineers |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |

### **Level 3 ‚Äì User evaluation**: Does the product positively support users‚Äô thoughts, feelings, knowledge, and behaviors?

### Why is this level of evaluation important?

Once an AI product is functioning correctly (Level 1\) and engaging users as intended (Level 2), the next step is to ask: Is this product actually changing how users think, feel, or act in ways that are in line with the product‚Äôs intended purpose? This level is essential because users‚Äô psychological and behavioral changes often serve as early indicators of whether a product is likely to achieve its long-term development goals (e.g., improving health outcomes or educational gains). Compared to full-scale impact evaluations, these user evaluations are faster and cheaper, and they allow product developers to iterate rapidly based on real-world feedback. 

At this stage, evaluations may focus on outcomes such as:

* **Cognitive Outcomes:** Are users gaining new knowledge or correcting misconceptions? Do they demonstrate improved skills or decision-making ability as a result of using the AI? 

  * *Example constructs: users‚Äô comprehension, reflection, reasoning, and perceived clarity or understanding during interaction.*

* **Affective Outcomes:** How does the product make users feel? Do users report feeling supported, motivated, and capable after interactions, or are there indications of frustration, confusion, or emotional distress? 

  * *Example constructs: mood, sense of belonging, perceived empathy, trust, or comfort interacting with AI.*

* **Behavioral Outcomes:** Are users taking small but meaningful actions (e.g., asking more questions, trying out recommended behaviors) that would predict their longer-term development?

  * *Example constructs: users‚Äô acquisition, recall, and application of factual or procedural information, and observable behaviors (e.g., asking more questions, trying out recommended behaviors) that are proxies for longer-term development outcomes.*
